Use ACF and PACF plots: AR(p) shows PACF cutting off at lag p with ACF tailing off; MA(q) shows ACF cutting off at lag q with PACF tailing off; ARMA shows both tailing off. Formally, minimize AIC = 2(p+q) − 2ln(L) or BIC = ln(n)(p+q) − 2ln(L) over a grid, e.g., p,q ∈ {0,…,5}. With n=200, prefer BIC since it penalizes complexity more heavily and reduces overfitting risk. Fit each candidate with exact MLE (e.g., statsmodels ARMA or R's arima), collect AIC/BIC, select the model with minimum BIC. Verify the chosen model by checking that residuals are white noise via Ljung-Box test (fail to reject at lags 10–20) and that AR/MA roots lie outside the unit circle. If AIC and BIC disagree, prefer the BIC selection for short series. Check parameter redundancy: if an AR root and MA root nearly cancel, reduce order. The result is typically a low-order model (p+q ≤ 4) for most real-world 200-point series.